From: nosnitch <nosnitch@local>
Subject: [PATCH] AirSnitch Patch 3 Step 1: reject duplicate MAC across BSSes

When a STA attempts to associate with a MAC that is already
associated on any other BSS on the same hostapd instance, deauth
it rather than accepting. This defeats the cross-BSSID port
stealing primitive on multi-SSID APs.

The 500 ms roaming grace window is enforced by the nosnitch
daemon using ubus events (see Patch 3 Step 4), which lets
legitimate 802.11r roams proceed.

--- a/src/ap/ieee802_11.c
+++ b/src/ap/ieee802_11.c
@@ -nnn,6 +nnn,25 @@ static void handle_assoc(struct hostapd_data *hapd,
 			      int reassoc)
 {
+	/* AirSnitch Patch 3 Step 1: cross-BSSID duplicate MAC rejection.
+	 * Block the case where an attacker holds a victim's MAC on BSS
+	 * A while associating with it on BSS B — which poisons the
+	 * bridge MAC-to-port table and redirects the victim's downlink
+	 * to the attacker. */
+	{
+		size_t i;
+		for (i = 0; i < hapd->iface->num_bss; i++) {
+			struct hostapd_data *other = hapd->iface->bss[i];
+			if (other == hapd)
+				continue;
+			if (ap_get_sta(other, mgmt->sa) != NULL) {
+				wpa_printf(MSG_INFO,
+					"AirSnitch: MAC " MACSTR
+					" already on BSS %s, rejecting on %s",
+					MAC2STR(mgmt->sa),
+					other->conf->iface, hapd->conf->iface);
+				hostapd_drv_sta_deauth(hapd, mgmt->sa,
+					WLAN_REASON_UNSPECIFIED);
+				return;
+			}
+		}
+	}
+
 	/* ... existing association handling ... */
 }
